        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Compulsory acquisition, also called resumption, is when a government or authorised government entity takes ownership of private property without the owner's consent, for a declared public purpose. In Queensland, this is governed by the Acquisition of Land Act 1967 (Qld). Authorities that can acquire property include the State Government, Brisbane City Council, TransLink, Queensland Rail, and entities such as Cross River Rail authority."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I object to the compulsory acquisition of my Queensland property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. When you receive a Notice of Intention to Resume (NIR), you have the right to lodge a formal objection with the Land Court of Queensland. Valid grounds include that the acquisition is not for a genuine public purpose, or that the area being acquired is greater than what is actually needed. Strict time limits apply, so you should engage a solicitor experienced in resumption law as soon as you receive an NIR."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How is compensation calculated for compulsory acquisition in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Compensation for compulsory acquisition in Queensland is based on the market value of the land at the time of acquisition, plus disturbance costs such as legal fees, valuation fees, and relocation expenses, plus solatium, which is a payment recognising the involuntary nature of the sale. Both the acquiring authority and the owner can commission independent valuations. If the parties cannot agree, the matter goes to the Land Court for determination."
      }
    }
  ]
