      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Compulsory Acquisition of Property in Queensland: What Owners Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Receiving a Notice of Intention to Resume is serious. Here is how the resumption process works in Queensland, what rights you have, and how compensation is determined.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Compulsory acquisition, known in Queensland as resumption, is one of the most significant things that can happen to a property owner. The government or a government-authorised entity takes ownership of your property without your agreement, for a declared public purpose, and you have no right to refuse the transfer of title. What you do have are rights around the process, the grounds on which you can object, and the compensation you are entitled to receive. Understanding those rights early is the difference between an acceptable outcome and leaving a significant amount of money on the table.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal framework in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Compulsory acquisition in Queensland is governed by the Acquisition of Land Act 1967 (Qld). This Act sets out the process that acquiring authorities must follow, the rights of affected property owners, and how compensation is to be assessed and paid. Any acquisition that does not follow this process can be challenged.</p>

      <p>The entities authorised to compulsorily acquire property in Queensland include the State Government, Brisbane City Council, and statutory bodies with specific enabling legislation. Infrastructure projects typically involve authorities created specifically to deliver them, such as Cross River Rail Delivery Authority, Queensland Rail, or TransLink. Each of these bodies has resumption powers derived from the Acquisition of Land Act and their own enabling legislation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Notice of Intention to Resume</h2>
      <p>The formal resumption process begins with the acquiring authority issuing a Notice of Intention to Resume (NIR). This is published in the Queensland Government Gazette and served on affected landowners. Receiving an NIR does not mean the acquisition has happened. It is the starting point of a process that includes a mandatory objection period.</p>

      <p>The NIR will describe the land being acquired, the public purpose for which it is needed, and the authority proposing to acquire it. It will also state the objection period, which is typically 30 days, although this should be confirmed in the specific notice you receive. Do not assume you have more time than the notice states.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Your right to object</h2>
      <p>Property owners have the right to lodge a formal objection to the Land Court of Queensland during the objection period stated in the NIR. Objections must be based on valid grounds under the Act. The most common valid grounds are that the acquisition is not for a genuine public purpose, or that the area of land being acquired is greater than what is actually necessary for the stated purpose. Objections cannot be based simply on not wanting to sell, or on the compensation amount being insufficient, because compensation is dealt with separately.</p>

      <p>The Land Court hears objections and makes a recommendation to the relevant Minister. The Minister can then decide to proceed with the acquisition, modify it, or abandon it. In practice, objections that successfully establish that land beyond what is needed is being taken have led to acquisitions being reduced in scope. Objections challenging the public purpose are harder to succeed on, but not impossible.</p>

      <p>Strict time limits apply. If you receive an NIR, engage a solicitor with compulsory acquisition experience immediately. Missing the objection period means you cannot formally challenge the acquisition through the Land Court, regardless of how strong your grounds might have been.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How compensation is assessed</h2>
      <p>Compensation for compulsory acquisition in Queensland has three components. The first is market value, which is the price the land would achieve in an open market between a willing buyer and a willing seller, assessed as at the date of acquisition. The second is disturbance costs, which cover expenses caused by the acquisition: legal fees, valuation costs, relocation expenses, and in some cases business losses where a business is affected. The third is solatium, a payment that recognises the involuntary nature of the sale and the disruption to the owner's life. Solatium is calculated as a percentage of the market value, up to a capped amount.</p>

      <p>Both the acquiring authority and the owner can engage independent registered valuers to assess the market value. The authority will provide its own valuation and make a compensation offer. If the owner believes the offer is inadequate, they can reject it and commission their own valuation. If the parties cannot reach agreement, the matter goes to the Land Court, which makes a binding determination on compensation.</p>

      <p>The cost of your valuer and legal representation in the negotiation and Land Court process is generally recoverable as part of your disturbance costs if you achieve a better outcome than the authority's initial offer. This means there is real incentive to obtain your own expert advice rather than accepting the first offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What Brisbane property owners near infrastructure corridors should know</h2>
      <p>Brisbane has significant infrastructure investment under way and in planning, including Cross River Rail, Brisbane Metro extensions, and upgrades to major road corridors. Properties in the path of or immediately adjacent to these projects may carry some level of acquisition risk, either for the land itself or for easements over part of the land.</p>

      <p>When buying or selling property near a known infrastructure corridor, a title and planning search should include a check for any registered taking or proposed taking notices. Sellers have disclosure obligations if they are aware of an NIR that has been issued over the property. Buyers should not assume that proximity to a project automatically means acquisition risk, because many properties near projects are not in the acquisition footprint, but it is worth verifying through a search rather than leaving it to assumption.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if you receive an NIR</h2>
      <p>The single most important step is to engage a solicitor with demonstrated experience in Queensland compulsory acquisition law immediately. Not a general property solicitor who handles conveyancing, but one who has specific experience in resumption matters, valuations, and the Land Court process. The difference in outcome between an owner who engages the right advice early and one who accepts the authority's initial offer without independent review is frequently substantial.</p>

      <p>Beyond legal representation, you should engage a registered valuer independently to assess your property's market value before engaging substantively with the authority's valuation. Do not wait for the authority's offer to arrive before getting your own valuation, because having an independent assessment ready from the outset puts you in a stronger negotiating position from the beginning.</p>

